-- by Brian Bockelman</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='12027#1335555266'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2012-04-27T19:34:26+00:00">Apr 27, 2012 07:34 PM UTC</time> by <b>Sarah Williams</b><a class="anchor" name="1335555266">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Marco, that is the files in user homedir. This ticket is about the globus tmp directory, /var/lib/globus/gram_job_state

Mat,  Brian is working with the folks running our condor submitter ( John Hover and Jose Cabellero ), and with Jaime Frey to figure out why so many of our jobs are left in TWO_PHASE_END. It looks like a scalability issue on the condor_g side, and may be addressed in condor 7.7.6.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='12027#1335554772'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2012-04-27T19:26:12+00:00">Apr 27, 2012 07:26 PM UTC</time> by <b>Marco Mambelli</b><a class="anchor" name="1335554772">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>The cleanup scripts and the jobmanager look into different directories in the user home dir. I opened a ticket&#58;
<a href='https&#58;//ticket.grid.iu.edu/goc/12053' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//ticket.grid.iu.edu/goc/12053</a>

Marco</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='12027#1335554274'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2012-04-27T19:17:54+00:00">Apr 27, 2012 07:17 PM UTC</time> by <b>Matyas Selmeci</b><a class="anchor" name="1335554274">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Sarah,

Did the workarounds Brian gave you solve your problems? Do you need any more help with anything?

Thanks,
-mat</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='12027#1335198578'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2012-04-23T16:29:38+00:00">Apr 23, 2012 04:29 PM UTC</time> by <b>echism</b><a class="anchor" name="1335198578">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Software Team,

Please examine the issue in this ticket.

Thank you,
Elizabeth</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='12027#1335197580'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2012-04-23T16:13:00+00:00">Apr 23, 2012 04:13 PM UTC</time> by <b>Sarah Williams</b><a class="anchor" name="1335197580">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>I&#39;ve discussed the situation with Brian Bockelman last week, at that time he said&#58;
&#34; I see 47k Globus jobs, of which 25k are in the state &#34;TWO_PHASE_END&#34;.  This means that Globus is waiting for the Condor-G at BNL to acknowledge it is ready to finish the job.  These acknowledgements at BNL are queued up in Condor and they might not be going out fast enough to keep up.

If you do a yum update, you&#39;ll get a version of the CE that cleans these jobs up automatically after 4 hours instead of leaving them around indefinitely.

Also, if you update to the latest osg-cleanup (and enable/run it), these jobs will be deleted regardless.  I recommend to not use the one prior to 3.0.9 due to bugs.

47k Globus jobs results in 94k files in a directory.  If something is periodically scanning through that directory (say, usatlas4 sending a GT2 job once an hour and firing up a fresh globus-job-manager for jobmanager-fork), it could thrash the page cache and result in the badness you see.

Also, tomcat is taking 2GB of RAM. Switch to osg-info-services and you don&#39;t have to run tomcat anymore.  osg-info-services is a cronjob and will have a much lower footprint.  &#34;</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='12027#1335197446'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2012-04-23T16:10:46+00:00">Apr 23, 2012 04:10 PM UTC</time> by <b>OSG-GOC</b><a class="anchor" name="1335197446">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>[by Sarah Williams]

osg-gk.mwt2.org is an OSG 3.0.8 CE, expected to upgrade to 3.0.9 shortly. /var/log/globus/gram_job_state had 30K files in it, and is extremely slow to ls.  We experience extremely high load spike (2K or more ) every hour when one of our users starts a new grid manager and it scans this dir.  We have only 6124 running jobs, and that wouldn&#39;t seem to me to need 30K files in globus tmp.  We are running osg-cleanup with a cleanup time of 4 days, and I have manually checked that none of the files has a modify date more than 4 days old.</pre></div><legend>Similar Recent Tickets <small>modified within the last 30 days</small></legend><div id="similar_tickets"><p class="muted">No similar tickets found.</p></div>
</div>
<script type="text/javascript">
function reset_anchor() {
    $("#updates .selected").removeClass("selected");
    var urls = document.location.toString().split('#'); 
    var anchor = urls[1];
    if(anchor) {
        $("a[name='"+anchor+"']").parents(".update_description").addClass("selected");
    }
}
function submitspam(ticket_id) {
    myret = confirm("Would you like to close this ticket as a security ticket, and submit the ticket content to akismet?");
    if(myret == true) {
        $.ajax("viewer/processspam?id="+ticket_id).done(function() {
            window.location.reload();
        });
    }
}

$(function() {
    reset_anchor();
    var ADDITIONAL_COOKIE_NAME = 'gocticket';
    var options = { path: '/', expires: 365};

    if(window.opener && window.opener.name == "gocticket_list") {
        v = $.cookie("closewindow");
        if(!v) {
            $("#closewindow").attr("checked", "checked"); //on by default
        } else {
            if(v == "checked") {
                $("#closewindow").attr("checked", "checked");
            }
        }
        $("#closewindow").click(function() {
            $.cookie("closewindow", $(this).attr('checked'), options);
        });
    } else {
        $("#closewindow_area").hide();
    }
    function updateTimeago() {
        $("time").timeago();
        setTimeout(updateTimeago, 30*1000);
    }
    updateTimeago();
    $(".description").focus(expand_description);
});
</script>
